Myasthenia gravis: A chronic autoimmune neuromuscular disease that weakens the muscles responsible for swallowing, eye movement, and breathing.
Guillain-Barre syndrome: An autoimmune disorder that affects the peripheral nerves, causing weakness, numbness, and tingling.
Stroke: A disruption of blood flow to the brain, resulting in neurological damage that can cause a variety of symptoms, including nausea, dysphagia, diplopia, and scotoma.
Brain tumor: A mass of abnormal cells in the brain that can cause a variety of symptoms, including nausea, dysphagia, diplopia, and scotoma.
Multiple sclerosis: A chronic autoimmune disease that affects the central nervous system, causing a variety of symptoms, including nausea, dysphagia, diplopia, and scotoma.

Meningitis: An inflammation of the membranes that surround the brain and spinal cord, caused by infection or other factors, and can cause a variety of symptoms, including nausea, dysphagia, diplopia, and scotoma.
Encephalitis: An inflammation of the brain, caused by infection or other factors, and can cause a variety of symptoms, including nausea, dysphagia, diplopia, and scotoma.
Botulism: A rare but serious illness caused by a toxin produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum, and can cause a variety of symptoms, including nausea, dysphagia, diplopia, and scotoma.
Lyme disease: A bacterial infection caused by the Borrelia burgdorferi bacterium, and can cause a variety of symptoms, including nausea, dysphagia, diplopia, and scotoma.
Nutritional deficiencies: A lack of essential nutrients, such as vitamin B12, can cause a variety of symptoms, including nausea, dysphagia, diplopia, and scotoma.
